SIMPLE: inveigle
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inveigle
<hw>In*vei"gle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Inveigled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Inveigling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Prob.
fr. F. <ets>aveugler</ets> to blind, to delude, OF. <ets>aveugler</ets>,
<ets>avugler</ets>, <ets>avegler</ets>, fr. F. <ets>aveugle</ets> blind,
OF. <ets>aveugle</ets>, <ets>avugle</ets>, properly, without eyes, fr.
L. <ets>ab</ets> + <ets>oculus</ets> eye. The pref. <ets>in-</ets> seems
to have been substituted for <ets>a-</ets> taken as the pref. F.
<ets>⟦agrave⟧</ets>, L. <ets>ad</ets>. See <er>Ocular</er>.]</ety>
<def>To lead astray as if blind; to persuade to something evil by
deceptive arts or flattery; to entice; to insnare; to seduce; to
wheedle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet have they many baits and guileful spells⟦br⟧
To <qex>inveigle</qex> and invite the unwary sense.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inveiglement</ent>⟦br⟧
